               <interp inst="t18771022-780" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18771022"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18771022-780" type="date" value="18771022"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18771022-780-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-780-18771022 t18771022-780-offence-1 t18771022-780-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>780. <persName id="def1-780-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-780-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-780-18771022" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-780-18771022" type="surname" value="VOGHT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-780-18771022" type="given" value="JOHAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-780-18771022" type="occupation" value="seaman"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHAN VOGHT</hi> (20)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18771022-780-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18771022-780-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18771022-780-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp>, Feloniously wounding <persName id="t18771022-name-196" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-196" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-196" type="surname" value="BUSS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-196" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-196" type="occupation" value="sailor"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18771022-780-offence-1 t18771022-name-196"></join>Edward Buss</persName>, with intent to do him grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DIXON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution; and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORACE AVORY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-197" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-197" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-197" type="surname" value="BUSS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-197" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD BUSS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">interpreted</hi>). I am a sailor on board the San Paulis, which the prisoner also belonged to—one evening, I cannot say the date, I went to a public-house, and the prisoner came in afterwards—he quar<lb></lb>relled—I told him to be quiet, and we left to go to my vessel—when we got near the water-side the prisoner began to quarrel with another man—I said "Be quiet," and then he struck me—I fell to the ground and received several blows on the head and arms—I felt I was cut—I was carried on board ship, and afterwards to the hospital.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> The quarrel in the public-house was between his ship<lb></lb>mates, and the prisoner went between them—I can't say whether to help them fight or not—I only said to the prisoner "Be quiet"—I struck him once while in the public-house with my hand—we had a quarrel before that, and I struck him because he interfered between the, other men—I do not think I am a stronger and bigger man than he—we all went out together to go to the ship—I did not have any row with him on the way, hut he quarrelled with the others—I did not seize him by the collar—I told him to be quiet—I catched hold of him in front by his breast—we were then on the quay—I seized him because I wanted to make him quiet—I don't know what he had bought, but he had a bundle in his hand of different things—he began to strike me—he did not say "Leave me alone"—I have not seen what he struck me with—he struck with his right hand—I cannot say what the bundle was in his left hand; it was too dark to see—I will swear I never struck him only once, when I said—I didn't catch hold of him; I only had my hand like that (<hi rend="italic">describing</hi>) against his breast—we had come over in the same ship as shipmates—we were not good friends; he was always at something against me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I did not try to push the prisoner into the water.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-198" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-198" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-198" type="surname" value="TRICKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-198" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES TRICKER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Inspector of Thames Police</hi>). I heard cries of "Police" on this night, and on going to the place I saw a ship's boat—I went to the passage, walked up the steps, and. at the stairs' head at the top of the landing-place, five yards from there, I saw the prosecutor lying on his hack and bleeding from the head—there were seven or eight foreigners round him, all belonging to the same ship—I had the prosecutor taken down to the boat, and the prisoner was taken on board also, and then on to the ship—I found the man had lost much blood, and was very weak—I did not know he had been stabbed, but finding the man was bleeding from the neck, I took this scarf off his neck, and saw a large wound in the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220046"></xptr>
               <p>neck—I said "Where is the knife, Johan?"—he said "In the water"—I did not find it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> The prisoner complained of being struck—I said so before the magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-199" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-199" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-199" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-199" type="given" value="WM"></interp>WM. HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am house surgeon at the Poplar Hospital—the prose<lb></lb>cutor was admitted on the 18th September—he had been bleeding very much; his clothes were saturated with blood—he had an incised wound on the left side of his head, on the back of his neck, and on his right forearm—the wound in the neck extended down to the spinal column, about 1 1/2 inches long—I should not like to say whether it penetrated—he had partial paralysis of the left side—he was in danger—the wounds could have been inflicted by a knife—he has not quite recovered from the paralysis—I think he will.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">The Prisoner's Statement before the Magistrate.</hi> He kicked me in the stomach, and struck me on the neck—he wouldn't leave me alone—I said "Let me alone," and he wished to throw me in the water—I said "Leave me alone, in the name of the Father and Son"—he wanted to drown me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18771022-780-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
